commit 7ab36138889c52d2e23baa25b917286834504cc7
Author: kenjiuno <h8mastre@gmail.com>
Date:   Mon Jan 19 13:08:47 2015 +0900

    Make sure WinSparkle's windows are always toplevel
    
    In a somewhat peculiar wx API choice, wxDialog with NULL parent is made
    a child of the (main) toplevel window unless the wxDIALOG_NO_PARENT flag
    is used. That was not the intent of this code, WinSparkle windows are
    meant to be parent-less. Use wxDIALOG_NO_PARENT explicitly.
    
    This wouldn't matter under normal conditions, because WinSparkle is
    meant to show only one window, but it is possible to get it into a state
    when it shows two during second launch of the host application: one will
    be AskPermissionDialog. If the user doesn't dismiss it and explicitly
    checks for updates, the regular UpdatesDialog will appear - and without
    wxDIALOG_NO_PARENT, would become a child of modally-shown
    AskPermissionDialog. When the users dismiss AskPermissionDialog
    afterwards, WinSparkle's UI will be in inconsistent case, leading to
    asserts and eventually failure to shut down the UI thread.
    
    This fix is still not perfect: interaction with UpdatesDialog are lost
    after the user dismisses AskPermissionDialog. This fix "only" makes this
    corner case safe, but not ideal from UX point of view.
    
    Fixes #44.

